This is a sequence of corporate governance moves that is honestly new to me=
:=09Do   some stuff that is, let us say, arguably fraud-adjacent.=09Get cau=
ght, in an  enormously public and embarrassing way.=09Announce=C2=A0that yo=
ur board has hired a high-powered law firm to  conduct a review of what you=
 did.=09Announce that actually you are just  shutting down the business.=09=
Obviously you don=E2=80=99t need the board investigation or the fancy law f=
irm.=09You don=E2=80=99t even need a board.=09Bye everyone!=09Announce that=
 you changed your mind and are not shutting down.=09Come back to work with =
no board investigation and no board.Does that work? Is that anything? Sort =
of a board cleanse? What do you have at the end of that process? I truly do=
 not know, like I said, this is all pretty new to me. But I  think a lot ab=
out questions of  who controls a company.=C2=A0In some=C2=A0theoretical sen=
se, the board of directors controls the company; it has the ultimate decisi=
on-making authority and can hire and fire executives. Traditionally, if the=
 executives do a very bad thing they might expect to get fired.This is less=
 true of startups where the chief executive officer is also the founder and=
 largest shareholder and public face of the company, and where the board mo=
stly serves to advise the founder-CEO, but it is still=C2=A0somewhat=C2=A0t=
rue of them. Both Uber Technologies Inc.=E2=80=99s and WeWork=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0boards managed to fire their founder-controller-CEOs over various embarr=
assments. Even where the CEO is the biggest shareholder and controls the bo=
ard, the board has some independent fiduciary duty to do right by the other=
 shareholders and stakeholders of the company; in times of crisis it has an=
 obligation to exercise control.But what I am asking here is, is there some=
 level of crisis that is so complete and so embarrassing that the board wil=
l skip right past crisis management to =E2=80=9Cflee for your lives=E2=80=
=9D? =E2=80=9CWell, there=E2=80=99s nothing really to save here, we=E2=80=
=99re getting out and we never want to hear about this again=E2=80=9D? =E2=
=80=9CWe can=E2=80=99t fire you, we quit=E2=80=9D? If so is that =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0good? It=E2=80=99s not good, but is it something? If you are the foun=
der-CEO, do you at least get total control of your company back, free from =
the interference of a board that would otherwise feel some obligation to in=
vestigate and make changes?Here=E2=80=99s more on the wildest media story, =
and due diligence story, and corporate-governance story, of the last few we=
eks:Ozy Media said it wouldn=E2=80=99t shut down after all, days after its =
board said the embattled digital-media startup was ceasing operations amid =
growing questions over the company=E2=80=99s business practices.Ozy Media C=
hief Executive Carlos Watson said on NBC=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CToday=E2=80=9D =
show Monday morning that the company would resume operations, calling it Oz=
y Media=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CLazarus moment,=E2=80=9D a reference to a follow=
er of Jesus who is raised from the dead in the biblical Gospel of John. =E2=
=80=A6Ozy Media=E2=80=99s board said last week it had hired the law firm Pa=
ul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton and Garrison LLP to =E2=80=9Cconduct a review o=
f the company=E2=80=99s business activities.=E2=80=9D That investigation is=
 no longer ongoing, according to a person familiar with the matter.Not beca=
use the board decided the investigation was unnecessary, but because=C2=A0t=
he board members decided that=C2=A0they were=C2=A0unnecessary.=C2=A0As of F=
riday there were two board members, Watson and Michael Moe, and:On Monday, =
a person with knowledge of the matter said that the Paul, Weiss investigati=
on of Ozy will not go forward, because the Ozy board members who commission=
ed the law firm are no longer with the company.In general if you are the CE=
O of a company it is bad when the board is unhappy enough to commission a f=
ancy law firm to =E2=80=9Cconduct a review of the company=E2=80=99s busines=
s activities.=E2=80=9D One approach might be to try to make the board happi=
er. But possibly the better approach is to make the board=C2=A0unhappier, s=
o they say =E2=80=9Cnever mind, I=E2=80=99ve seen enough=E2=80=9D and you d=
on=E2=80=99t have to do the review? We are talking about making the best of=
 a bad situation here and this is definitely a creative solution.Also here=
=E2=80=99s a wild anecdote about Watson allegedly throwing a book at an emp=
loyee:One anonymous staffer told me Watson literally threw a book across th=
e room at her. The book was The Hard Thing About Hard Things: Building a Bu=
siness When There Are No Easy Answers.Good throwing book! Hardcover, 304 pa=
ges, about a pound,=C2=A0intellectually hefty. When you clonk someone on th=
e head with =E2=80=9CThe Hard Thing About Hard Things,=E2=80=9D they know t=
hat you are serious about building a transformative business and willing to=
 make difficult managerial decisions, like the decision to throw a book at =
them.
