      PFOF
   =20
 =20
I have tried to  write about this  before, but one weird thing in debates a=
bout payment for order flow=C2=A0is, if you were going to =E2=80=9Cban=C2=
=A0payment for order flow,=E2=80=9D would you ban=C2=A0payment for order fl=
ow, or would you ban internalization? The way the stock market works right =
now is that if you are a retail customer looking to buy or sell a stock, yo=
ur order generally does not go to the stock exchange: Your broker routes it=
 to one of a handful of big electronic market makers, who generally sells y=
ou the stock (or buys it from you) at a price that is slightly better than =
what=E2=80=99s available on the public exchange (=E2=80=9Cprice improvement=
=E2=80=9D), and pays your broker for the chance to do so (=E2=80=9Cpayment =
for order flow=E2=80=9D). You could ban that whole thing and make brokers s=
end retail orders to the stock exchange. Or you could leave everything in p=
lace and just ban the=C2=A0payments=C2=A0from market makers to brokers; the=
 brokers would just have to send orders to the market makers who offered th=
e best price improvement, not the ones who pay.I think either is a more or =
less plausible answer. If your concerns with payment for order flow are abo=
ut conflicts of interest (retail brokers route orders to market makers who =
pay), or about gamification (payment for order flow enables free trading an=
d probably too much of it, and higher payment for options orders gives brok=
ers incentives to push options on customers), or about execution quality (h=
igher payment for order flow means less price improvement), then I suppose =
banning payment for order flow would make sense. If your concerns are about=
 opacity (so you want all orders to go to lit exchanges), or the market dom=
inance of a handful of market makers (so you don=E2=80=99t want them to get=
 all the retail orders), or about spreads on lit markets (so you don=E2=80=
=99t want retail orders to all be siphoned off to retail market makers, lea=
ving only toxic orders on the lit exchanges), then I suppose you would need=
 to ban internalization more broadly. Just banning payment for order flow w=
ould leave everything as it is right now except that, instead of paying Rob=
inhood Markets Inc. for retail orders, the market makers would get them for=
 free.There is a certain amount of vague talk about the Securities and Exch=
ange Commission =E2=80=9Cbanning payment for order flow,=E2=80=9D based mos=
tly on the fact that SEC Chair Gary Gensler goes around saying that he does=
n=E2=80=99t like it. My own  reading of Gensler=E2=80=99s statements is tha=
t his objection to payment for order flow is =E2=80=9Call of the above=E2=
=80=9D and that if he could wave a magic wand he=E2=80=99d probably want to=
 ban retail internalization, dark pools, everything. But that seems like a =
pretty hard thing to do and my guess is that=C2=A0if the SEC ever actually =
does anything here =E2=80=94=C2=A0not all=C2=A0that=C2=A0likely? =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0it will be more like banning payment for order flow than banning inte=
rnalization. (I have written before, for instance, that that would be fine =
for Robinhood.) But I don=E2=80=99t know and I suspect nobody else does eit=
her.Citadel Securities has a large business of market-making for retail ord=
ers, and that business appears to be good and lucrative, and I guess if the=
 SEC banned it that would be bad for Citadel Securities? (I mean, it=E2=80=
=99d be fine, the retail orders would go to the lit exchanges, and Citadel =
Securities would compete to fill them, and presumably its market-making bus=
iness on lit exchanges is also profitable, but there's a reason Citadel Sec=
urities wants to get those retail orders separately.) But if the SEC forbad=
e Citadel Securities from=C2=A0paying=C2=A0for those orders, that would obv=
iously be good for Citadel Securities? Because getting things free is bette=
r than paying for them? Anyway:Kenneth Griffin, the founder of Citadel Secu=
rities, said he would be =E2=80=9Cquite fine=E2=80=9D if payment for order =
flow was banned as the controversial practice comes under increasing scruti=
ny from securities regulators.=E2=80=9CPayment for order flow is a cost to =
me,=E2=80=9D Griffin said, addressing The Economic Club of Chicago on Monda=
y. =E2=80=9CSo if you=E2=80=99re going to tell me that by regulatory fiat o=
ne of my major items of expense disappears, I=E2=80=99m OK with that.=E2=80=
=9DYeah seems right. But Bloomberg News  adds something else he said:Griffi=
n said he would be =E2=80=9Cfine=E2=80=9D if that system disappeared tomorr=
ow, =E2=80=9Cso long as we leave the standard that execution quality is how=
 orders should be allocated among market-makers.=E2=80=9DI think the way to=
 read that is =E2=80=9Cbanning payment for order flow is good for Citadel S=
ecurities, but please don=E2=80=99t ban internalization.=E2=80=9D If the ru=
le is that brokers have to send retail orders to the market maker who offer=
s the most price improvement, then Citadel Securities is in the same place =
it is now: It just has to shift the money that it pays for order flow into =
price improvement. If the rule is that brokers have to send orders to excha=
nges and=C2=A0aren=E2=80=99t allowed to seek price improvement from market =
makers, then that will be a big shift in the market makers=E2=80=99 busines=
s. But that seems less likely.
