      Fake trades
   =20
 =20
Here is a good Securities and Exchange Commission enforcement action (and a=
 related criminal case) about the mechanics of rogue trading. The idea of r=
ogue trading is basically that you work for a bank or broker, and you think=
 =E2=80=9Chey I think this bond will go up=E2=80=9D or whatever, so you buy=
 a bunch of the bond with the firm=E2=80=99s money, and if in fact it goes =
up then you report a big profit and your bosses are happy and you get a big=
 bonus. And if it goes down you do the same trade again next week with twic=
e as much of your firm=E2=80=99s money. And if you keep getting it wrong, y=
ou keep upping your bets, and eventually when you get in trouble you get in=
 very big trouble indeed. The headline on the SEC=E2=80=99s press release i=
s =E2=80=9CSEC Charges Rogue Trader Who Bankrupted His Firm=E2=80=9D; that =
sort of trouble.Your firm obviously does not want you to do that and so it =
has systems in place to stop you. In this case, according to the SEC compla=
int, Keith Wakefield worked for a broker-dealer named IFS Securities Inc. a=
s a bond trader. Customers wanted to buy bonds from him, he would go source=
 the bonds, he=E2=80=99d buy them for IFS=E2=80=99s account and sell them t=
o the customer at a markup. He was=C2=A0not=C2=A0in the business of buying =
bonds for IFS=E2=80=99s account=C2=A0without=C2=A0a customer order lined up=
; he could only do =E2=80=9Criskless principal=E2=80=9D trades where his bu=
ying and selling offset. (For a while he=C2=A0was=C2=A0in the business of t=
rading for IFS=E2=80=99s account =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cbeginning in appro=
ximately 2013, IFS authorized Wakefield to engage in limited speculation of=
 Treasuries with IFS=E2=80=99s proprietary funds=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0bu=
t after he lost $215,000 on a trade, they shut that down and=C2=A0made him =
pay back the money.[3])=C2=A0So he could only trade for customers. And he a=
llegedly wanted to do rogue proprietary trades; specifically, he allegedly =
wanted to sell Treasury bonds short. How do you do that? Well, the basic me=
chanics are that you (1) sell some bonds for IFS=E2=80=99s account, and sim=
ultaneously (2) pretend to buy them from a client=E2=80=99s account. It loo=
ks like you are selling the bonds for a customer, not taking a short positi=
on. Then, when you want to close out your short, you (3) buy the bonds back=
 for IFS=E2=80=99s account and simultaneously (4) pretend to sell them to a=
 client. It looks like you are buying the bonds for a customer, not taking =
a short position. As far as your bosses know you are just doing riskless pr=
incipal trades to fill customer orders.=C2=A0This is sort of a weird move! =
When you pretend to sell the customer=E2=80=99s bond in step (2), your clea=
ring broker is going to expect to receive the bond. The clearing broker see=
s a sell order from a customer, no bond arrives, the broker calls you up an=
d says =E2=80=9Chey where=E2=80=99s that bond?=E2=80=9D What do you say? We=
ll the answer is pretty much that you tell the broker to wait a few days, t=
hen you do steps (3) and (4). You buy back the bond, close out your short, =
tell the clearing broker that you have an offsetting trade, and then say =
=E2=80=9Cwell, no need for you to get the bond anymore, everything=E2=80=99=
s back to flat.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Here=E2=80=99s the SEC=E2=80=99s description =
of Wakefield=E2=80=99s process:On June 20, 2019, Wakefield sold short a par=
 amount of $20 million Treasuries at a price of $103.25 to a real counter-p=
arty from an IFS proprietary account and reported that sale to Broker-Deale=
r 1. This was a real trade.=C2=A0That same day, Wakefield also falsely repo=
rted to Broker-Dealer 1 that IFS bought, from the IFS customer omnibus acco=
unt that cleared through Broker-Dealer 2, $20 million of the same Treasury =
security for its proprietary account at a price of $101.00. This was=C2=A0a=
 fake trade.Wakefield set the settlement date for both the real and fake tr=
ades as June 26, 2019. Between June 20 and June 26, 2019, IFS=E2=80=99s tra=
de blotter reflected a fictitious short term profit of $395,788.04, which r=
epresented the difference in trade prices between the real and fake trades.=
On June 26, 2019, at the time of settlement, Wakefield covered his short sa=
le position by purchasing a par amount of $20 million of Treasuries at a pr=
ice of $103.11 in an IFS proprietary account. This was a real trade.Wakefie=
ld then reported a fake sale of $20 million Treasuries at a price of $101.0=
0 from the IFS proprietary account to the IFS customer omnibus account at B=
roker-Dealer 2. This was a fake trade.Broker-Dealer 1 paired off the fake o=
ffsetting trades (20 million in par at a price of $101.00) from the Broker-=
Dealer 2 IFS customer omnibus account, and the fictitious short term profit=
 of $395,788.04 was reversed. However, IFS realized a proprietary profit of=
 $28,125=C2=A0on the actual trade.Nice work. He didn=E2=80=99t always make =
money though:Beginning in June 2019, Wakefield tried to recoup losses he ha=
d incurred by taking increasingly larger short positions in Treasuries.Howe=
ver, the Treasury market slowly turned against him as Treasury yields dropp=
ed, which caused Treasury bond prices to rise and Wakefield=E2=80=99s losse=
s from his unauthorized Treasury trades to escalate.Etc., until:During the =
week of August 5, 2019, certain of the counter-parties contacted IFS=C2=A0r=
egarding the firm=E2=80=99s failure to honor the trades that Wakefield had =
placed, and IFS=E2=80=99s CEO and others at the firm became aware of Wakefi=
eld=E2=80=99s unauthorized speculative Treasury trading.IFS terminated Wake=
field on August 8, 2019. IFS spent virtually all of its existing capital, a=
pproximately $5.3 million as of July 31, 2019, attempting to cover more tha=
n $24 million in losses on Wakefield=E2=80=99s failing trades. IFS filed fo=
r bankruptcy on April 24, 2020.=C2=A0
