rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">WeWork=E2=80=99s</a>=C2=
=A0boards managed to fire their founder-controller-CEOs over various embarr=
assments. Even where the CEO is the biggest shareholder and controls the bo=
ard, the board has some independent fiduciary duty to do right by the other=
 shareholders and stakeholders of the company; in times of crisis it has an=
 obligation to exercise control.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But what I=
 am asking here is, is there some level of crisis that is so complete and s=
o embarrassing that the board will skip right past crisis management to =E2=
=80=9Cflee for your lives=E2=80=9D? =E2=80=9CWell, there=E2=80=99s nothing =
really to save here, we=E2=80=99re getting out and we never want to hear ab=
out this again=E2=80=9D? =E2=80=9CWe can=E2=80=99t fire you, <em>we </em>qu=
it=E2=80=9D? If so is that =E2=80=A6=C2=A0good? It=E2=80=99s not good, but =
is it something? If you are the founder-CEO, do you at least get total cont=
rol of your company back, free from the interference of a board that would =
otherwise feel some obligation to investigate and make changes?</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/25241118.274768/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9venktbWVkaWEtc2F5=
