tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Here=E2=80=99s mor=
e</a> on the wildest media story, and due diligence story, and corporate-go=
vernance story, of the last few weeks:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Ozy Media said it wouldn=E2=80=99t shut down after all, days after =
its board said the embattled digital-media startup was ceasing operations a=
mid growing questions over the company=E2=80=99s business practices.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ozy Media Chief Executive Carlos Watson said on N=
BC=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CToday=E2=80=9D show Monday morning that the company w=
ould resume operations, calling it Ozy Media=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CLazarus mom=
ent,=E2=80=9D a reference to a follower of Jesus who is raised from the dea=
d in the biblical Gospel of John. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Ozy Media=E2=80=99s board said last week it had hired the law firm Paul, W=
eiss, Rifkind, Wharton and Garrison LLP to =E2=80=9Cconduct a review of the=
 company=E2=80=99s business activities.=E2=80=9D That investigation is no l=
onger ongoing, according to a person familiar with the matter.</p></blockqu=
ote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not because the board decided the investig=
ation was unnecessary, but because=C2=A0the board members decided that=C2=
=A0<em>they </em>were=C2=A0unnecessary.=C2=A0As of Friday there were <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25241118.274768/aHR0cHM6=
