cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">criminal case</a>) a=
bout the mechanics of rogue trading. The idea of rogue trading is basically=
 that you work for a bank or broker, and you think =E2=80=9Chey I think thi=
s bond will go up=E2=80=9D or whatever, so you buy a bunch of the bond with=
 the firm=E2=80=99s money, and if in fact it goes up then you report a big =
profit and your bosses are happy and you get a big bonus. And if it goes do=
wn you do the same trade again next week with twice as much of your firm=E2=
=80=99s money. And if you keep getting it wrong, you keep upping your bets,=
 and eventually when you get in trouble you get in very big trouble indeed.=
 The headline on the SEC=E2=80=99s press release is =E2=80=9CSEC Charges Ro=
gue Trader Who Bankrupted His Firm=E2=80=9D; that sort of trouble.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Your firm obviously does not want you to do that an=
d so it has systems in place to stop you. In this case, according to <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25241118.274768/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMS9jb21wLXByMjAyMS0yMDU=
ucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB56b68241" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the SEC complaint</a>, K=
eith Wakefield worked for a broker-dealer named IFS Securities Inc. as a bo=
nd trader. Customers wanted to buy bonds from him, he would go source the b=
onds, he=E2=80=99d buy them for IFS=E2=80=99s account and sell them to the =
customer at a markup. He was=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>in the business of buyi=
ng bonds for IFS=E2=80=99s account=C2=A0<em>without=C2=A0</em>a customer or=
der lined up; he could only do =E2=80=9Criskless principal=E2=80=9D trades =
where his buying and selling offset. (For a while he=C2=A0<em>was=C2=A0</em=
>in the business of trading for IFS=E2=80=99s account =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Cbeginning in approximately 2013, IFS authorized Wakefield to engage in l=
imited speculation of Treasuries with IFS=E2=80=99s proprietary funds=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but after he lost $215,000 on a trade, they shut that do=
wn and=C2=A0<em>made him pay back the money</em>.[3])=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">So he could only trade for customers. And he allegedly wan=
ted to do rogue proprietary trades; specifically, he allegedly wanted to se=
ll Treasury bonds short. How do you do that? Well, the basic mechanics are =
that you (1) sell some bonds for IFS=E2=80=99s account, and simultaneously =
(2) pretend to buy them from a client=E2=80=99s account. It looks like you =
are selling the bonds for a customer, not taking a short position. Then, wh=
en you want to close out your short, you (3) buy the bonds back for IFS=E2=
=80=99s account and simultaneously (4) pretend to sell them to a client. It=
 looks like you are buying the bonds for a customer, not taking a short pos=
ition. As far as your bosses know you are just doing riskless principal tra=
des to fill customer orders.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is =
sort of a weird move! When you pretend to sell the customer=E2=80=99s bond =
in step (2), your clearing broker is going to expect to receive the bond. T=
he clearing broker sees a sell order from a customer, no bond arrives, the =
broker calls you up and says =E2=80=9Chey where=E2=80=99s that bond?=E2=80=
=9D What do you say? Well the answer is pretty much that you tell the broke=
r to wait a few days, then you do steps (3) and (4). You buy back the bond,=
 close out your short, tell the clearing broker that you have an offsetting=
 trade, and then say =E2=80=9Cwell, no need for you to get the bond anymore=
, everything=E2=80=99s back to flat.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/25241118.274768/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWlud=
HMvMjAyMS9jb21wLXByMjAyMS0yMDUucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC56b68241" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">the SEC=E2=80=99s description</a> of Wakefield=E2=80=99s process:</p><b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On June 20, 2019, Wakefield sold sho=
rt a par amount of $20 million Treasuries at a price of $103.25 to a real c=
ounter-party from an IFS proprietary account and reported that sale to Brok=
er-Dealer 1. This was a real trade.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">T=
hat same day, Wakefield also falsely reported to Broker-Dealer 1 that IFS b=
ought, from the IFS customer omnibus account that cleared through Broker-De=
aler 2, $20 million of the same Treasury security for its proprietary accou=
nt at a price of $101.00. This was=C2=A0a fake trade.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Wakefield set the settlement date for both the real and fake tra=
des as June 26, 2019. Between June 20 and June 26, 2019, IFS=E2=80=99s trad=
e blotter reflected a fictitious short term profit of $395,788.04, which re=
presented the difference in trade prices between the real and fake trades.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On June 26, 2019, at the time of settlement=
, Wakefield covered his short sale position by purchasing a par amount of $=
20 million of Treasuries at a price of $103.11 in an IFS proprietary accoun=
t. This was a real trade.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wakefield then re=
ported a fake sale of $20 million Treasuries at a price of $101.00 from the=
 IFS proprietary account to the IFS customer omnibus account at Broker-Deal=
er 2. This was a fake trade.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Broker-Dealer =
1 paired off the fake offsetting trades (20 million in par at a price of $1=
01.00) from the Broker-Dealer 2 IFS customer omnibus account, and the ficti=
tious short term profit of $395,788.04 was reversed. However, IFS realized =
a proprietary profit of $28,125=C2=A0on the actual trade.</p></blockquote><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nice work. He didn=E2=80=99t always make money =
though:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Beginning in June 2019,=
 Wakefield tried to recoup losses he had incurred by taking increasingly la=
rger short positions in Treasuries.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">However=
, the Treasury market slowly turned against him as Treasury yields dropped,=
 which caused Treasury bond prices to rise and Wakefield=E2=80=99s losses f=
rom his unauthorized Treasury trades to escalate.</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Etc., until:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">During the week of August 5, 2019, certain of the counter-parties contac=
ted IFS=C2=A0regarding the firm=E2=80=99s failure to honor the trades that =
Wakefield had placed, and IFS=E2=80=99s CEO and others at the firm became a=
ware of Wakefield=E2=80=99s unauthorized speculative Treasury trading.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">IFS terminated Wakefield on August 8, 2019. IFS=
 spent virtually all of its existing capital, approximately $5.3 million as=
 of July 31, 2019, attempting to cover more than $24 million in losses on W=
akefield=E2=80=99s failing trades. IFS filed for bankruptcy on April 24, 20=
20.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"=
